answers.body_markdown:
Yes, the _[ArrayList](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/20/docs/api/java.base/java/util/ArrayList.html)_ is a class, it extends _[AbstractList](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/20/docs/api/java.base/java/util/AbstractList.html)_, and implements _[List](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/20/docs/api/java.base/java/util/List.html)_&amp;mdash;among others.

Here is the _[OpenJDK](https://openjdk.org/)_ source-code for _[ArrayList](https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/blob/master/src/java.base/share/classes/java/util/ArrayList.java)_, _[AbstractList](https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/blob/master/src/java.base/share/classes/java/util/AbstractList.java)_, and _[List](https://github.com/openjdk/jdk/blob/master/src/java.base/share/classes/java/util/List.java)_.

The _ArrayList_ is not a _final_ class, so, yes, it can be sub-classed.  
An _ArrayList\&lt;String\&gt;_ is the same class&amp;mdash;just, declared with a generic-type parameter.

The _ArrayList_ class is what&#39;s called a _parameterized class_; it makes use of a _[generic-type](https://docs.oracle.com/javase/tutorial/java/generics/index.html)_, introduced in Java 5. 

When you create an instance of _ArrayList_, without specifying a _generic-type_, you&#39;re essentially passing in _Object_; as opposed to _String_, in this case.

For example, the following two statements are equivalent.

```java
ArrayList list = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
```
```java
ArrayList&lt;Object&gt; list = new ArrayList&lt;&gt;();
```

Generally, you would want to supply the _generic-type_, although it is not required.

There is a subtle error in your code, in the inner for-loop.

```java
if (!star.contains(str.charAt(seq) + str.charAt(seq + 1)))
```

When adding _char_ values, they will not be concatenated&amp;mdash;like _String_ objects.

Instead they will be converted to _int_ values.

In this case, if I use _&quot;abc&quot;_ as an example, on the first iteration, the value being passed to _star#contains_ is _195_, and not _&quot;ab&quot;_.  

Here is an evaluation.

```java
str.charAt(seq)     = &#39;a&#39; /* 0x61, 97 */
str.charAt(seq + 1) = &#39;b&#39; /* 0x62, 98 */
                          /* 97 + 98 = 195 */
```

Thus, a _false_ is being returned.

There are a few ways to correct the error.

The most common approach would be to use a _[String#valueOf](https://docs.oracle.com/en/java/javase/20/docs/api/java.base/java/lang/String.html#valueOf(char))_ call, which will return a _char_ value as a _String_.  
As a note, since adding a _String_ and a _char_ together will result in concatenation, you only have to parse one of the values.

```java
if (!star.contains(String.valueOf(str.charAt(seq)) + str.charAt(seq + 1)))
```

Your _star#add_ call is already achieving the same result by using an initial empty-string.

```java
star.add(&quot;&quot; + str.charAt(seq) + str.charAt(seq + 1));
```

Is equivalent to 

```java
star.add((&quot;&quot; + str.charAt(seq)) + str.charAt(seq + 1));
```

As a recommendation, although it is not required, you can create a local variable to hold the concatenated value, since you&#39;re using it more than once.

In this example, I created a new variable, _String string_.

```java
Scanner sc = new Scanner(System.in);
//System.out.print(&quot;enter test case no&quot;);
String string;
int t = sc.nextInt();
for (int test_case = t; test_case &gt;= 1; test_case--) {//System.out.print(&quot;enter length of string&quot;);
    int n = sc.nextInt();
    //System.out.print(&quot;enter string&quot;);
    String str = sc.next();
    ArrayList&lt;String&gt; star = new ArrayList&lt;String&gt;();
    for (int seq = 0; seq &lt; str.length() - 2; seq++) {
        //System.out.print(&quot;inside for loop&quot;);
        string = String.valueOf(str.charAt(seq)) + str.charAt(seq + 1);
        if (!star.contains(string)) star.add(string);
    }
    System.out.println(star.size());
}
```

Input

```none
1
3
abc
```

Output

```none
1
```

